## CI/CD Setup Guide in GitHub
This guide outlines how to configure CI/CD pipelines in GitHub using two different methodologies: Jenkins as a GitHub App or a GitHub Actions Self-Hosted Runner.
------------------------------
## 1. Jenkins as a GitHub App
For enhanced security, all new Jenkins instances should use a GitHub App registration instead of a standard user or dummy user account.
## Why this matters
A GitHub App allows up to 15,000 API calls per hour, whereas a user or dummy account is restricted to only 5,000 calls per hour and is highly susceptible to rate-limiting or throttling by GitHub.
------------------------------
## 1.1. Configuration Steps in GitHub

Note: You must be an Organization Administrator or possess explicit permissions to manage GitHub Apps to complete these steps.

## 1.1.1. Create the GitHub App

   1. Navigate to your GitHub Organization main page.
   2. Click Settings ➔ Developer Settings ➔ GitHub Apps.
   * Direct Link: https://github.com/organizations/<YOUR_ORG>/settings/apps
   3. Click the New GitHub App button.

## 1.1.2. Configuring the GitHub App Settings
Fill out the required administrative fields:

* GitHub App name: Enter a descriptive identifier (e.g., Jenkins - <team_name>).
* Homepage URL: Input https://netapp.com.
* Webhook Section: Uncheck the Active checkbox.
* Reasoning: Because OpenLab is contained within a private internal network and is not publicly accessible via the open internet, GitHub cannot route inbound push events directly to your Jenkins instances.

Configure the explicit granular permissions required by the Jenkins integration plugin:

* Commit statuses: Set to Read and Write (allows Jenkins to post pass/fail icons onto pull requests).
* Contents: Set to Read-only (allows Jenkins to fetch the Jenkinsfile and repository source tree).
* Note: If your pipeline automatically tags releases or pushes code changes back to the repository, elevate this permission to Read & write.
* Metadata: Set to Read-only.
* Pull requests: Set to Read-only.

Under the Subscribe to events section, enable all event checkboxes, then click Create GitHub app.
## 1.1.3. Generate the Private Key
Once GitHub redirects you to the newly created app management page, scroll down and click Generate a Private Key. This downloads an asymmetric .pem cryptography file to your local computer. This key represents Jenkins's master passport to GitHub; store it safely, as it cannot be redownloaded if lost.
## 1.1.4. Convert the Private Key
The downloaded certificate must be converted into a standard PKCS#8 format that the Java Virtual Machine runtime environment natively understands. Run the following command in your local terminal (replace the example filename with your downloaded file):

openssl pkcs8 -topk8 -inform PEM -outform PEM -in your-app-private-key.pem -out converted-github-app.pem -nocrypt

## 1.1.5. Install the Application

   1. From your GitHub App settings page, click Install App in the left sidebar menu.
   2. Locate your Target Organization and click the corresponding Install button.
   3. Choose the repository scope. Selecting All Repositories ensures that the app automatically inherits permissions for all current and future codebase repositories.

## 1.1.6. Record the GitHub App ID

   1. Navigate to your GitHub Organization page (https://github.com/<YOUR_ORG>).
   2. Go to Settings ➔ Installed GitHub Apps.
   3. Click Configure next to your custom app name, then click App Settings.
   4. Locate and copy the numeric App ID string for the subsequent Jenkins setup.

------------------------------
## 1.2. Configuration Steps in Jenkins## 1.2.1. Plugins to Install
Ensure your Jenkins controller has the following core community extensions installed via Manage Jenkins ➔ Plugins:

* Credentials Plugin: Natively handles safe secret injection within controllers.
* GitHub Branch Source Plugin: Connects Jenkins directly with GitHub App credential specs.

## 1.2.2. Set up the GitHub App Credential

   1. Open Jenkins and navigate to Manage Jenkins ➔ Manage Credentials.
   2. Under the Stores scoped to Jenkins section, select the Jenkins storage provider link.
   3. Click Global Credentials (Unrestricted), then click Add Credentials in the left sidebar.
   4. Fill out the credential parameter fields exactly as follows:
   * Kind: Select GitHub App from the dropdown list.
      * ID: Define a clear text unique identifier (e.g., github-app-team-token).
      * Description: Leave blank or add an optional reference note.
      * App ID: Paste the numeric App ID recorded from Step 1.1.6.
      * Key: Click the input block, open your local converted-github-app.pem file, copy its exact text contents, paste them here, and click OK.
   
## 1.2.3. Set up the GitHub Organization Project Item

   1. From the Jenkins dashboard home screen, click New Item.
   2. Type an item name, select GitHub Organization from the type grid, and click OK.

## 1.2.3.1. Project Credentials Setup
On the item configuration screen, locate the Projects config area. Select the newly generated GitHub App identification credential from the Credentials dropdown menu. This grants Jenkins the authorization required to query your GitHub Org space.

* Note: Ensure the API Endpoint and Owner fields match your enterprise GitHub deployment configurations. Be mindful of the 15,000 hourly API call limit during large automated testing patterns.

## 1.2.3.2. Configure Scan Organization Triggers
Because the active webhook trigger configuration was disabled in Step 1.1.2 (due to private OpenLab isolation), Jenkins cannot receive real-time commit push notifications from the public cloud. Instead, Jenkins must regularly query GitHub to check for code changes.

* Configuration: Change the default setting from 1 day to a faster interval. We recommend setting this parameter to 5 minutes to ensure engineers don't face long delays waiting for pipeline executions after pushing code.

## 1.2.4. Trigger the Scan Organization Event
Jenkins will immediately initiate an automated indexing discovery sweep across all target repositories granted during the app installation. If the scanning sweep discovery process does not run automatically, manually click Scan Organization Now in the item sidebar menu.

* Automation Metric: If any discovered repository contains a valid Jenkinsfile at its root level directory, Jenkins automatically registers that repository, maps its active branches, and builds the initial deployment pipeline.

------------------------------
## 2. GitHub Actions Self-Hosted Runner
If you prefer using native GitHub Actions over Jenkins, you can deploy self-hosted worker loops directly onto local Virtual Machines (VMs) or physical machines inside OpenLab.
## 2.1. Configuration Steps in GitHub
Determine your operational runner scope strategy first:

* Repository Scope (Visible only to one unique repository): Navigate to Repository ➔ Settings ➔ Actions ➔ Runners.
* Direct Link: https://github.com/<ORG>/<REPO>/settings/actions/runners
* Organization Scope (Shared across all repositories inside your Org): Navigate to your Organization Main Page ➔ Settings ➔ Actions ➔ Runners.
* Direct Link: https://github.com/<ORG>/settings/actions/runners

Once you reach the runner control center screen, proceed with the following actions:

   1. Click the Add runner button.
   2. Choose your hosting environment's operating system platform (Linux, macOS, or Windows) along with the target hardware processor architecture (e.g., x64, ARM64).
   3. GitHub will display a step-by-step terminal command script snippet sequence customized with an ephemeral authentication token. Keep this browser tab open.

## 2.1.1. Understanding Groups and Labels
Once a self-hosted runner successfully connects back to GitHub, you can organize it using two management features:

* Groups: Provide administrative boundary access controls. You can bundle multiple machines at the organization level and restrict them so only specific private repositories can run jobs on them.
* Labels: Functional metadata tags applied to individual machines. GitHub Action scripts inspect these labels to route specific workloads to machines with matching characteristics (e.g., routing a machine learning model compilation task specifically to a runner tagged with a gpu label).

------------------------------
## 2.2. Configuration Steps on Your Local Machine
Log directly into your isolated OpenLab terminal server destination instance to run the installation scripts:

* ⚠️ Mandatory Security Rule: You must not run the GitHub Actions configuration or execution runner scripts as the system root user profile. For security reasons, the GitHub Actions runner application will explicitly refuse to execute and fail if started with root privileges.
* Execution Pattern: Copy and run each terminal command line sequence displayed on your open GitHub browser settings screen exactly as shown.
* Troubleshooting Note: If the startup script encounters system dependency failures due to missing operating system packages, the installer output will print out the exact command lines required to install the missing platform packages.

------------------------------
## 2.3. Configuring Your GitHub Action Workflow File
To route automated software integration tasks directly to your custom internal OpenLab infrastructure hardware, add a runs-on declaration block into your .github/workflows/ci.yml project files.

# This is a basic workflow file designed to get you started with native GitHub Actionsname: CI
# Controls when the automation workflow engine triggers executionon:
  # Triggers the execution loop on code push or pull request actions targeted at the main branch
  push:
    branches: [ main ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

  # Allows administrators to manually trigger this pipeline run from the GitHub Actions user interface tab
  workflow_dispatch:
# A workflow execution run is constructed from one or more distinct job blocks that run in parallel or sequencejobs:
  # This workflow defines a single automated compilation task block labeled "build"
  build:
    # Explicitly defines the destination runner machine required to process this job
    # The 'self-hosted' label instructs the engine to bypass GitHub infrastructure and use your OpenLab machine
    runs-on: self-hosted

    # Steps represent a sequentially ordered list of tasks executed inside the runner shell environment
    steps:
      # Step 1: Checks out your repository source tree under the $GITHUB_WORKSPACE path so subsequent steps can read it
      - uses: actions/checkout@v2

      # Step 2: Executes a standard single-line shell statement using the runner machine's default shell interpreter
      - name: Run a one-line script
        run: echo Hello, world!

      # Step 3: Executes a multi-line shell command sequence via standard multi-line pipe formatting blocks
      - name: Run a multi-line script
        run: |
          echo Add other actions to build,
          echo test, and deploy your project.
