## Managing Resources for Jenkins Dynamic Agents and Containers
#########################################################
There are two critical factors to consider when configuring resources for a container or a dynamic Jenkins Kubernetes agent.
------------------------------
## 1. Where to Add Resource Information in the Kubernetes Agent YAML
Resource specifications are declared directly within the resources block of the container definition inside your Kubernetes Pod template. This template can be included as an inline block or as a referenced file in your Jenkinsfile.
## Operational Definitions

* requests: Represents the guaranteed resource block reserved for the container during the Jenkins agent creation phase. The pod will not schedule unless a worker node has this capacity available.
* limits: Provides elastic operational headroom. If your build process experiences a sudden processing spike, it can leverage additional resources on the host worker node up to this maximum ceiling (if available).

## Best Practice Policy
Always enforce explicit, baseline requests and limits configuration parameters across all Jenkins build agent templates. This baseline must provide just enough capacity to run normal continuous integration workloads.
If an automated build pipeline routinely fails due to Out-Of-Memory (OOMKilled) errors, development teams must profile their compilation lifecycle using real-time dashboard metrics on the Rancher Portal to determine the precise operational footprint and update the Jenkinsfile configurations accordingly.
## Production Pod Specification Example

apiVersion: v1kind: Podmetadata:
  name: frontendspec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: images.my-company.example/app:v4
    resources:
      requests:
        memory: "128Mi"
        cpu: "150m"
      limits:
        memory: "256Mi"
        cpu: "350m"
  - name: log-aggregator
    image: images.my-company.example/log-aggregator:v6
    resources:
      requests:
        memory: "128Mi"
        cpu: "150m"
      limits:
        memory: "256Mi"
        cpu: "350m"

------------------------------
## 2. Deciphering Resource Units in Kubernetes
Understanding how Kubernetes quantifies infrastructure processing allocations prevents compilation bottlenecks and scheduling execution failures.
## Understanding CPU Units
Limits and requests for processing resources are calculated strictly using CPU units. In a Kubernetes ecosystem, 1 CPU is equivalent to:

* 1 vCPU / Core across public cloud provider environments (e.g., AWS, Azure, GCP).
* 1 Hyperthread on bare-metal Intel server processor architectures.

Fractional compute requests are fully supported. Specifying a requests.cpu parameter value of 0.5 guarantees your container exactly half the processing capacity of a container requesting 1 CPU.

* The Expression 0.1: Natively identical to 100m (read as "one hundred millicpu" or "one hundred millicores").
* API Constraints: Decimal definitions like 0.1 are automatically converted to 100m by the master API system. Precision finer than 1m is strictly prohibited. For clarity and consistency, using the millicore string form (e.g., 100m) is preferred.
* Absolute Metric Rule: Compute parameters are explicitly calculated as an absolute quantity, never a relative percentage. A value of 0.1 CPU represents the exact same processing capability whether running on a basic single-core server or an enterprise 48-core host node.

## Understanding Memory Units
Limits and requests for RAM allocations are calculated strictly in Bytes. Memory values can be expressed as a standard integer or a fixed-point number utilizing one of two shorthand scale suffixes:

| Metric Type | Suffix Format (Base-10 / Decimal) | Suffix Format (Base-2 / Binary Power-of-Two) |
|---|---|---|
| Kilobyte | k | Ki |
| Megabyte | M | Mi |
| Gigabyte | G | Gi |
| Terabyte | T | Ti |
| Petabyte | P | Pi |
| Exabyte | E | Ei |

💡 Conversion Example: The following notation entries represent approximately the same mathematical memory storage value:
128974848 bytes ≈ 129e6 ≈ 129M ≈ 123Mi

------------------------------
## 3. Profiling Your Right-Sized Resource Footprint
Determining accurate capacity metrics requires monitoring live runtime execution footprints rather than guessing.
## Real-Time Metric Telemetry via Rancher
Live performance metrics for ephemeral, dynamic Jenkins worker agent pods are captured during the lifecycle of an active pipeline run and can be inspected directly on the Rancher Portal.
## How to Access and Apply Telemetry Data

   1. Access Provisioning: To view telemetry dashboards, teams must submit their designated ng group identifier to the platform team. This grants your engineers structured, limited-access privileges to your specific namespaces inside the Rancher Portal interface.
   2. Analysis Strategy: Review the real-time performance curves displayed within the Rancher Pod Metrics snippet during heavy execution loops (such as compilation, test assembly, or container image creation). This data maps out your right-sized baseline target allocations.
   3. Proactive Collaboration: If your specialized workloads require massive resource footprints, contact the platform team in advance. Early notification allows us to scale out regional physical node capacity and ensure high resource availability for all teams.

## References

* For deep-dive architectural data on managing container runtimes, review the official Kubernetes handbook: Resource Management for Pods and Containers.

